commit_list.message:
interface and organization cleanup

the convenience function `GetTerminalInfo` wasn't convenient enough; now
it returns a `Terminfo`. furthermore, the raw database, which
unfortunately is the best place to store the capability names without
re-allocating them all the time, is no longer private, so it can be
accessed from a `Terminfo`.

also moved said convenience functions into their own file.

updated examples to match new interface.

Adding examples and more information about the game & its ends
Whoops, Illustrator doesn't add linefeeds when copying text
Reorganizing file structure so we can use HTML5 hash-free paths in Angular

Move uuid directive into directives module

Also, relatedly, move some requirements around. Mostly for demo purpose.
Let's get it started in here
Make the main event channel accessible to handlers
Toggle logging in store.Rebuild instead of store.Open

Use hardcoded consts for ComponentStore log actions

Iota computes the value (granted, quite predictably) every time the
source is compiled, which won't do if we accidentally cause it to
compute different values. Not that our current store is very robust
anyway, but still.

Quit after shutting down hurr durr

Turns out the 'break' in our select wasn't breaking the for loop!

Implement basic component store

The component store allows storing arbitrary data in what amounts to a
KVS where the keys are a pair (Entity, Component) where Entity in our
case is a UUID and Component is a string representing a particular
component type. Type safety is not handled by the ComponentStore API,
but may be... one day...

The existing registration/login handlers were reimplemented to use the
new ComponentStore. It seems to work well enough.

With only Set and Remove operations mutating the data in the
ComponentStore, it was simple enough to log every action to a *.gob file
using the gob encoding package. Any types used as components (i.e. the
actual data we end up with) usually need to be Registered with gob
before they can be used. This is done in LoadWorldState, but like other
things may be better handled in the ComponentStore API. Conceptually,
however, the API currently knows nothing about any types, so it makes
sense, after a fashion, to have the already type-aware LoadWorldState()
take care of it (I mean, it even has access to the main WorldState
struct!)

Be further warned that changes are only persisted when
ComponentStore.Set() is called. This means that although you may have a
convenient pointer to a struct stored in there, and it will indeed be
saved, just changing an attribute in the struct won't be reflected until
you save it again. This means that some attributes can be treated as
transient, but they will indeed get persisted as soon as somebody else
persists something. We currently do this with Player.ConnId, but it's
very much unsafe and the practice should probably be abandoned.

More gotchas, pitfalls, and recognitions of bad decisions on that front
will be forthcoming, I'm sure.

Finally, we have a serious problem with lingering goroutines. I tried
and failed to come up with a working fix with quit channels and what
not, and I have reason to believe the culprits are some goroutines
somewhere of which I was not previously aware. Again, more to come.

We can technically use any net.Conn type, not limiting us to TCP. So why
